= Papen and Hindenburg

At the meeting between [+ nsdap_leader +], Göring, Papen, Meissner, and Hindenburg’s son, everyone—except Oskar—backs the appointment of [+ nsdap_chancellor +] as Chancellor. Meissner’s shift is especially significant; once wary, he now lends weight to the schemers’ influence. The President, who once vowed never to appoint [+ nsdap_chancellor +], begins to waver.

The next morning, Papen presents his plan to Hindenburg. His call for Schleicher’s dismissal meets no resistance. But when he names [+ nsdap_chancellor +] as the preferred successor—rather than himself, as Hindenburg would prefer—the old man recoils. He remains scornful and deeply distrustful of [+ nsdap_chancellor +], deeming him fit, at best, to oversee the postal ministry.

